Juricakov Dec 22, 2022

There was a problem hiding this comment.

Choose a reason for hiding this comment

The reason will be displayed to describe this comment to others. Learn more.

👏 for knowing about the in operator.

Just a heads up, we typically use hasOwnProperty because it is more precise to what you're actually trying to figure out. in will return true if the object has this property anywhere in the prototype chain, meaning it ends up including stuff like method names.

const emptyObj = {};

"toString" in emptyObj; // true
Object.prototype.hasOwnProperty(emptyObj, "toString"); // false

There is a cleaner way to write this initialization using the nullish coalescing ?? operator. It returns the right hand side if the left hand side is null or undefined

undefined ?? "bar" // bar
null ?? "bar" // bar
"foo" ?? "bar" // foo

That said, I'm also somewhat confident that this check if tickets exists is unnecessary, typescript knows tickets will exist because input.type is "MANUAL"

Step 2: Switch to the base branch of the pull request.

git checkout master
